RBAC Policy DSL Compiler
========================

A Domain-Specific Language (DSL) compiler designed to statically analyze, verify, and optimize Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) policies. 

By modeling role inheritance as a directed graph and applying mathematical set theory, this compiler acts as a strict security gatekeeper. It prevents logical vulnerabilities—such as infinite inheritance cycles and Transitive Separation of Duty (SoD) violations—from ever reaching production environments.


FEATURES
--------
* Custom Lexer & Parser: Transforms human-readable .rbac policy files into a structured Abstract Syntax Tree (AST).
* Graph-Based Cycle Detection: Utilizes Depth-First Search (DFS) to map role hierarchies and detect infinite inheritance loops.
* Separation of Duty (SoD) Verification: Evaluates transitive inheritance up to N levels deep to strictly enforce CONFLICT rules and prevent toxic privilege combinations.
* AST Optimization: Automatically strips redundant transitive inheritance and duplicate permissions to generate a clean, highly efficient execution tree.
* Context-Aware Error Reporting: Pinpoints exact line and column numbers for syntax and semantic violations.


ARCHITECTURE PIPELINE
---------------------
The compiler processes policies through four strict phases. If any phase fails, compilation is immediately aborted to guarantee security.

1. Lexical Analysis: Regex-based tokenization of the input stream.
2. Syntax Analysis: Recursive descent parsing to validate EBNF grammar and build the AST.
3. Semantic Analysis: Static security auditing (Undefined Parents, Duplicate Roles, Cycles, SoD).
4. Optimization: Redundancy removal and AST compression.


INSTALLATION & USAGE
--------------------
Prerequisites:
* Python 3.8+ (No external libraries required; relies entirely on standard libraries).

Running the Compiler:
To compile and verify a policy file, run the main.py script via the command line, passing your target .rbac file as an argument:

    python main.py path/to/your/policy.rbac

Example Output (Successful):
    === RBAC DSL Static Security Compiler ===
    [*] Phase 1: Lexical Analysis...
        -> Success: Generated 42 tokens.
    [*] Phase 2: Syntax Parsing...
        -> Success: AST built with 5 roles.
    [*] Phase 3: Semantic Security Analysis...
        -> Success: Policy is mathematically secure.
    [*] Phase 4: AST Optimization...
        -> Success: Redundancies stripped.
    === COMPILATION COMPLETE ===


LANGUAGE SYNTAX GUIDE
---------------------
The custom DSL uses a clean, brace-enclosed syntax designed specifically for security administrators.

Keywords: ROLE, INHERITS, PERMIT, CONFLICT

Example .rbac file:

    // Define base roles and their permissions
    ROLE Teller { PERMIT process_deposit, withdraw_funds }
    ROLE Approver { PERMIT audit_transactions }

    // Enforce Separation of Duty (SoD)
    CONFLICT Teller, Approver

    // Single Inheritance
    ROLE SeniorTeller INHERITS Teller { PERMIT vault_access }

    // Multiple Inheritance (Will trigger an SoD Violation!)
    ROLE BranchManager INHERITS SeniorTeller, Approver { PERMIT fire_employee }


TESTING
-------
The project includes a comprehensive unittest suite that evaluates individual modules (Unit Tests) and the end-to-end CLI pipeline (Integration Tests).

To run the full test suite:

    python -m unittest test_compiler.py -v


